title: Anycubic Linear Plus Supported Board Mount

description.text:
This is a board mount for the Anycubic Linear Plus Delta to replace the acrylic mount supplied with the printer.

The original acrylic mount broke on mine due to poor gluing and even after repairing it it provided very poor support to the board. I tried a few designs from thingiverse but ultimately was unhappy with them because all of the ones I tried gave very poor access to the Power wires for the heated bed. This design provides support to the board and provides excellent wire access by moving the board a little more towards the center of the printer.

After mounting the board in this Thing I was able to reuse the acrylic face plate but the USB and Power plugs are deeper than they were but they still work fine.

I made the board mounting holes undersized so you could drill them to the size and type of bolt you want to use. I used some old computer mounting screws I had laying around. because of this I would suggest at least 4 perimeters to allow for drilling.

This is a larger mount so I am unsure if it will fit the pulley version as I do not have one to test.

title: Raspberry Pi Zero Stem Case v2.1

description.text:
Following on from our Raspberry Pi Zero / Zero W Stem Case we've created a new version with many improvements.

This is a case for the Raspberry Pi Zero/Zero W with the "Stem" by zerostem.io - a PCB shim that turns it into a dongle.

The enclosure has been redesigned to be a much better, all around enclosure with two interlocking parts, rather than a box with a simple lid.
​
The case is now 2mm shorter allowing for a much better fit for the Pi Zero with Stem.
​
There are two bases and four top sections allowing for options to access the HDMI and USB ports and/or the header or completely enclosed.
​
All versions of the case leave just enough access to the micro SD card for a pair of tweezers or small pliers
​
The USB port for power is intentionally enclosed as it's redundant with the Zero Stem and should not be used.
​
The case is still designed to be glued together as there is insuficient room to create reliable snap-fit lugs internally.

As always; the SketchUp file is included.

v2.1

  • Updated top_b2.stl to provide better clearance around the header.
  • Updated top_a1.stl to provide better clearance around the HDMI and USB ports.
  • Updated top_a2.stl to provide better clearance around the header, HDMI and USB ports.
  • Updated SketchUp file.

With my fat thumbs, I have trouble getting the wire to be in the right position when crimping Dupont and other connectors. This design uses an alligator clip and a small printed piece to allow the wire to be correctly positioned and held long enough to squeeze the tabs over the insulation. Make sure the part is attached to the alligator clip jaw that doesn't have the center tooth. This tooth must clamp on the wire.

This set includes parts to hold the following connectors:

Male and Female 2.54mm dupont connectors
Male and Female 2.54mm JST-SM connectors

Also handles are provided to attach to the alligator clip to keep the clip from twisting and to make the operation easier.

My collection of the best Things posted for the week of 8/28/17:
https://www.thingiverse.com/LoboCNC/collections/best-of-the-week-8-28-17

This is the second week of my experiment with crowd-sourced curation. I've looked at every single Thing posted from 8/28/17 through 9/3/17 and selected what I think are the best Things according the criteria listed below. This posting here is sort of a meta-Thing to help people find this collection. Let me know what you think of this idea in the comments section.

If you like this concept, please "Like" this Thing to help others find it. You can also "Like" the collection itself. And if you really like this idea, create your own Best of the Week collection. I've tagged this with "BOTW" and "Curation" and would encourage others to use the same tags.

My Selection Criteria

What I look for:

  1. Things that are unique
  2. Things that are well executed
  3. Things that are of general interest
  4. Things that are well presented
  5. Things that make me smile

What I pass over:

  1. Cover images that are a rendering (i.e.: no photo of a real print)
  2. Accessories for very specific products (e.g.: for GoPro Hero, Samsung Galaxy 7, etc.)
  3. Things based on copyrighted material
  4. 3D printer parts (just too many, too specific and too boring)

Firstly, my goal is to go through the 400+ things posted each week and only present the 10% or so that I feel a reasonable percentage of people might find interesting. I've taken the easy route - given my selection criteria, I am able to include almost everything that meets them in 3-4 pages (12 things/page).  I want to keep the number  of pages down to something easily scan-able.  10 pages is to many, but I'm thinking most people will be willing to look through 3-4 pages.  Winnowing it down to a single page (12 things) would give it a more exclusive feel and maybe thus give designers something to strive for, but I'm inclined to keep it a little more broad but easily viewable.  I'll look forward to see what other people think and move in whatever direction there seems to be a consensus.

Dopo mesi che stampavo senza raffreddare il materiale mi sono deciso a scaricare un modello per montare una ventola. L'ho usata per parecchio tempo ma non sono mai stato molto soddisfatto un po per l'estetica (perchè il pezzo era studiato per un'altra stampante) e un po perchè non svolgeva bene il suo lavoro. Mi sono deciso a creare un convogliatore apposito per il mio estrusore e dopo un paio di mesi (lavorando nei tempi morti della settimana) sono riuscito ad avere il prodotto finito.

Il convogliatore è studiato per una ventola radiale 40x40x10 mm che si monta su un estrusore di questo tipo https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:961630
Il pezzo è composto da due pezzi da incollare tra di loro mediante colla da modellismo o cianoacrilica. Ho deciso di stamparlo dividendo il pezzo in 2 metà in modo da eliminare eventuali supporti.
La ventola si fissa al convogliatore mediante 2 viti M2, ed il convogliatore con 2 viti M3 al corpo dell'estrusore.

title: Hictop Prusa Y axis Motor Holder & endstop mount

description.text:
Hi All,

after my work at school with the Makerbot Replicator 2 and 5 I bought this Chinese? Prusa clone to play with at home.I was just curious to the Prusa concept and wanted to work with open source hardware.

So far super happy!

EXCEPT:
The Y motor mount. The Y motor turns pretty hot and causes with the belt tension it's mount to warp. Acrylic isn't that heat-resistant I guess. This design prevents that.
I remixed it from JMecky's design with an Endstop (I saw that somewhere else) so that the endstop is not anymore on the moving bed. (looks much more durable to me) I remixed it in Tinkercad. (Nice and easy)

Printed in ABS (because of the heat of the motor) and so far, no problems. Belt is supertight and everything is running smoothly.

It fits right in the holes. So no extra drilling required as I saw by some other y mount- models.

Good Luck!

description.text:
A 10mm thick EF lenscap with extra grippiness to it minus some of the slow printing problems at some level.*4 Included is a "sharp" version (Shown in the photos) and a version with filleting around the corners that helps with print speed.

I don't have any EF lenses yet but these sure mount on my adapters1 well. As far as I can tell (Since I'm not a Canon user) most Canon lenses don't have pokey tabs or aperture levers that would interfere with this thing.3 It could probably be a tiny bit thinner but then it won't act as an impact absorbing crumple zone if in some horrible thing were to happen and your lens decided to commit suicide by jumping out of your camera bag. The fit on these caps will be initially very tight most likely, but once you cycle them on and off the bayonet then they'll loosen up to an acceptable "just right."

Also there's no distracting logos or other stuff to remind you that I made this. Unfortunately that also means no text telling you these are for EF. That also solves itself in that I don't have a F version of these lenscaps (Nor do I plan on making a F version any time soon, unless someone wants to pay me to do that. You can't get me leaving Nikon any faster than I already am.)

1 Fotodiox adapter for Nikon G type lenses, which has the blue tabs. And a crummy Neewer adapter which has aluminum on the body side of the mount for that crummy feeling when you mount it onto a Speedbooster2 or an actual Canon body (which I don't own so I don't know how horrible it'd feel). Seriously get yourself a brass adapter, not even Boeshield will make these things slip on smoothly. I'll let you know about my adventures here since I am converting over to EF mount with all my F mount glass anyways.

*2 For the curious: I run Olympus flavored Micro Four Thirds.

*3 If you own a Nikkor 50mm f/1.2 of some sort, the large tab in the rear protrudes greatly. Do not try to mount that onto an EF Speedbooster Ultra, it will hit the felt and the plastic shield behind it. I trimmed mine back so I have circumcised the lens to allow for it t mount. This also means this cap most likely will not mount with an unmodified lens. It does happily mount on a Sigma 18-35 f/1.8 along with many other lenses as they don't have too many protrusive bits and the aperture lever happily sits inside the adapter anyways.

*4 For some reason there are lens caps that have awesome knurling on them. The problem is awesome knurling also means unawesome print times because of the many small radii or small features.

Also I highly recommend you to print this in PLA and then do an in place annealing on your heated bed. See this video that I made regarding this subject:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZoNQGlyFWy8

The annealing process is so good with plain old Inland PLA that I can take scraps of support material and then viciously bend it (Rectilinear grid) and it doesn't snap apart. If anything I have to flex it a lot until the bonds break at the points and then aggressively yank and pull at it before the little thin strands snap. title: fast xy calibration 100 mm x 100mm x 3mm

description.text:
print in under 25min !!!

100 mm x 100 mm x 3mm ( x/y/z) calibration square
x + y mark

steps for calibration X /Y axis:

1.Connect to your printer via a USB connection (direct to computer or Octoprint, etc.)

  1. Issue the M503 command

  2. Scroll back through the output of the M503 command and look for the M92 output. e.g. "echo: M92 X88.0 Y99.0 Z2560.00 E100.0"

  3. measure top + bottom x and y eg. xtop: 100.4 + xbottom 100.2 -> xAverage 100.3 ,yleft: 100.3 + yrigth 100.5 -> yAverage 100.4

  4. use this formula to determine new M92 values:
    New M92 value = Desired movement / Actual movement Current M92 value
    So for example, New M92 for X (87.74) = 88    100/100.3
    So for example, New M92 for Y (98.61) = 99*100/100.4

  5. Create the new M92 command by replacing the X and Y values above with the new calculated values: "M92 X87.74 Y98.61 Z2560.00 E100.0"

  6. Place this line in the Startup GCODE in your slicer. In Simplify3D this is placed in the Scripts --> Starting Scrip area. In Slic3r this is in Printer Settings --> Custom G-code.

  7. Re-slice the Calibration square

  8. Re-print the Calibration square

  9. Mark and measure the new calibration square as in steps 4 above. Average the distances for X and Y. These should now be closer to 100.0mm.

  10. If you are satisfied with the results, you are done!

  11. If the distances are not as close to 100mm as you desire, if not happy with results, repeat the calibration process.

Note: When you change material, you should re-test dimensions, and may need to re-calibrate your M92 values.

description.text:
This is a dual 50mm Fan mod for the Creality CR10 nicknamed the "Batfang."

It uses the stock hotend shroud, and press fits into place. It fits very snug at the current settings and does not move.

This fang has 3 parts, the body and two covers to reduce the support necessary for printing. It uses the 4 original screws from the stock part cooler to hold these covers on.

Please note that this upgrade is not recommended if you are going to be printing sequenced prints "one after another", as it adds significant mass to the print head, and will likely collide with parts on the hot bed if you do not print multiple prints "all at once."

If however you print single parts, or multiples "all at once" there should be no issues.

As of right now this is a working prototype. I have tested this part in a less "finished" state with the differences being in the corner radii (as you'll see in the images) and so far it has worked flawlessly.

I am sharing this in it's current state, hoping that the community will adapt and improve it as they see fit.

:) Happy Printing

Router mounting plates have a large hole in them for the bit to sit up from the table surface. This hole is intended to accommodate a plastic insert that has various inner holes to match the bit being used. For some reason, these inserts are stupidly expensive.

If you enter the OuterDiameter of your insert hole, the RimDiameter of the inner hole, and LipDepth of the insert, the OverallThickness you want this insert, and the BitDiameter of the center hole of the insert, you will get an STL that will print these at will. If you do not want a center hole, set BitDiameter to zero.

To begin with, use a caliper to measure the above values for your table, and tweak from there to get a perfect fit. I used PLA and they work great.

These are also good for making bandsaw table inserts, but you need to slice the insert first to use it.

BTW, this is a dirt simple SCAD program, so if you're looking to get your feet wet with SCAD, this is a good program to play with. I know this is pretty simple, but I didn't see one already out there for this purpose.

description.text:
First of all a big thx to Dovanzeijl for the Anet A6 x-carriage This model is heavily based on his Model!

The Problem

Calibrating my tronxy based sensor was a pain in the a... for me. Everytime i had to adjust the sensor to noozle height, i had to unscrew&screw the sensor, hope that it didnt move while fastening and so on.

My Solution

Here is the fix for me. The sensor is on a sled which is mounted on a rail. the sled can be raised and lowered whith turning the screw. The spring holds the sled under tension so it wont wobble around.

Works for me :) Hope it can help you too.

What you need

You need a heatbed spring, a 35mm M3 screw as the rotation axis and 2x M3 8mm screws for fixing the rail to the carriage.
For the BLTouch Adapter you need 2x M3 6mm additionally.
I recommend you weld in some Brass Knurl Nuts for a more stable/reliable setup

You have another sensor?

If you have another sensor, let me know. Maybe we can design a universal mount with different adapters for this design

description.text:
This dugout houses a 8x59mm One Hitter. 20
I made this out of convenience. It's really compact and incorporates a locking mechanism so that EVERYTHING is secure and won't be accidentally opened in your pocket or purse or wherever.

V3 - Added a channel for laying your one hitter on.

  • Cap can now be rotated out of the way and the Pipe can be removed without spillage.
  • Made the reservoir a little smaller as the walls were much too thin around it and was
    prone to separation.

V2-

  • Added more of a conical end to the Stash area. This lets EVERYTHING go to the bottom so that nothing is wasted.
  • Lid can now be swiveled so that you can get your One Hitter out without opening the container.
    -Little Indention that you can place the One Hitter on when not in use, Leave the hot end well over the edge ;)

Hope you enjoy it.
Also, don't forget to let the ceramic cool before placing it back into the dugout :) I like to print this in PLA since It's quite safe. ABS is toxic and I don't want to smoke anything that comes in contact with ABS. Just not worth the risk to me.

Printing Notes

I have uploaded this in parts so that if something goes wrong with one part of it, you won't have to print the whole dang thing again.

It is recommended that you print your Cap with 100% infill because it has a tendency to want separate the little plug on the cap. I know this could be remedied with a little offset, but l like the way it fits.

Also...Be sure to use the lowest layer height you can for your nozzle! Having the layer height course means that you could potentially get little bits of Tobacco/Herbs stuck in between the layers, and that's no fun :(

Important Notes

DO NOT FILL DUGOUT WITH TOBACCO/HERBS UNTIL YOU TEST FIT!
Every printer is different and what might work for me doesn't work for you. The Fitment is made to be tight, but it would be a real bummer if you got your Dry Content stuck with the lid on.

This goes without saying....but please be mindful with what filament you are printing this in. I personally have printed this in PLA. Reason? Well, it's pretty darn safe so that's good enough for me. I don't need anything getting contaminated.

title: Monoprice Maker Select V2 Tablet Mount

description.text:
I recently started using Printoid for OctoPrint with my Monoprice Maker Select and had to figure out where to put the Android tablet. Looked at what models were out there and decided this would be a good first 3D design project.

Got the basic shape from a wire mesh business card holder that I use as a tablet stand on my desk. Thought it might be nice if the mounts snapped onto the top of the printer frame. Made a couple of prototypes out of foam-core. Then started modeling in Onshape.

At first I just modeled the lower portion that would snap on to get the size right.While doing this I noticed it would slide back and forth really easily. I had recently seen a number of camera mounts that used little magnets to hold them in place so added holes for them on the bottom.

I also put in holes for some 1/4 inch threaded rod that I had. After printing the final mounts and adding the magnets I found I didn't really need the rods. So you can use them with or without the rods.

If you want to play around with it the Onshape model can be found at (https://cad.onshape.com/documents/a5b4b14806d07fe1153e7cfe/w/156376d5213f95c174466755/e/76b4fe2e482f0c9419610768).

Assembly

The magnets are just superglued in place. I used 6x3mm magnets I got on Amazon, (https://smile.amazon.com/gp/product/B073TLKCXK/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s01?ie=UTF8&psc=1).

With the threaded rod I used nylock nuts on the inside and cap nuts on the outside. Put the nylock nuts on first with plenty of space for the mounting brackets.Then put on the Cap nuts. Finally back the nylock nuts out until snug.

Finally I got the following right angle USB cables for the tablet that help keep things neat and tidy,
(https://smile.amazon.com/gp/product/B01COTBK7Q/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1).

description.text:
I like to keep a teacup of olive oil and a silicon brush near my stove. I can brush a little oil on pans to prevent sticking, on my ironware for seasoning after cleaning, and on bread as an alternative to butter. Endless uses! Alas, a horde of almost-microscopic kamikaze ants discovered my cup o' oil. It's not so much that I'm averse to sharing, but many drowned themselves in the oil, despoiling its vegetarian nature.

I'm going to try replacing the teacup with this ant-resistant chalice. A bowl in the bottom holds a little bit of water (or, perhaps, mineral oil) to dissuade the anties from raiding the delicious olive oil up top.

Two important notes: this should be printed using food-safe PLA and/or coated with a food-safe lacquer. While basic PLA isn't toxic, there's no guarantee otherwise that toxic dyes and colorings haven't been added to that spool you got for cheap from Joe's House o' Filament. Second, I've yet to see how PLA holds up to long-term exposure to oil and water. I'll update this when the piece has been in service a while.

Edit: I had some problems with the model leaking, but that seems to be related to my having set a rather large layer height in my slicer. So far, with a layer height of 0.1mm it seems to be working much better.

Notes:

I used 0.8mm wall thickness.

I couldn't get good adhesion without a raft on my Monoprice Maker Select V2 (Wanhao). It printed without a raft on my Monoprice Mini, but that piece had a design defect.

The bottom of the bowl has significant overhang. It printed without difficulty on both my printers without having to use supports.

I have included the FreeCAD source for your remixing pleasure.

Don't forget to use food-safe PLA.
Lacquer it after printing to keep it food-safe.

It's a simple FreeCAD design:

Create a cylinder for the base. Subtract a cylinder of 2mm smaller radius and 2mm shorter to make space for the water.

Another cylinder creates the stem. I found that the radius had to be big enough for the piece to remain stable during printing. That also helps the overhangs print without supports.

The bowl is just a hemisphere with a smaller hemisphere to hollow it out. I added height with a 2cm tall hollowed out cylinder so that my long-handled silicone brush would stay in the cup.

It a gimbal for my DIY Mavic pro build (scale 130% from original build http://diyrc.co.uk) and the runcam split cam.
I use 2x 2204 and one 2805 motor.

BASE STL COMING....

This display holder with magnetic base engages the strap-mounting features on a car headrest video monitor. The monitor was the secondary monitor in an RCA brand DRC79982 9" DVD player set.

I'm not too sure how common this monitor is or how useful others will find this project, but I was really proud of how securely the legs grabbed the strap loops... one of my favourite things about 3D printing is being able to graft things together that were never intended to be.

I'm using the monitor to display G-Codes on an old Emco Compact 5 CNC lathe I have, and I wanted it to mag-mount to the existing control panel on the lathe... so... a good excuse for a 3D printing project.

I drew this in Fusion 360. If I can figure out how to get a source file out of that I'll add it here.

title: PMDG NGX flaps for Saitek quadrant (Boeing 737)

description.text:
I designed this to use an axis from my saitek quadrant to control flaps on the PMDG 737 NGX, there are the 9 flaps positions (using the idle button for flaps full).
You need to cut to plastic part that prevent the blue lever to slide freely, you can then need to put a screw on the lever's arm (I used a wood screw) and use a spring going trough the 3D printed lever part and attached to that screw. Now you just need to lift the lever to change flaps position like on the real B737.

I used fsuipc to setup the flaps, you need to modify the max value of the axis to 20000 (default around 163384) so that the end ofthe axis stops at flaps 30.
Then setup the idle button for flaps max, and action when button release: flaps decr.

Let me know in the comments if there's any problem

Marshall Keychain

1) I found a jpeg image on Google and converted it into an SVG file on an online converter.
2) I extruded the 2D image (the SVG file) in 123D design.
3) Once the object was extruded, I created a square border to place the extruded image on.

description.text:
This is designed to cover a standard UK light switch and hold two Philips Hue dimmer remote controls. The original light switch is still accessible when the Hue remote is removed.

The Hue remotes are held in place with magnets behind the switch cover.

I have previously used the single Hue remote switch covers from cgcrute, and these worked very well.
Then we needed a switch cover to hold two Hue remotes, so I started by trying the double-remote remix from tuk485. Unfortunately our existing rocker switches protrude further (5mm) and prevent the Hue remote from lying flush. This together with a couple of other niggles led me to go back to basics, draw a fresh angular outline in SketchUp, copy the dimensions and key design features from cgcrute's single remote switch covers, and then use the great Round Corner extension from Fredo6 to round off the various edges and corners.

For the magnet, I chose to use the same as cgcrute used for his switch covers:
http://www.banggood.com/50pcs-N52-Super-Strong-Disc-Magnets-20mm-x-3mm-Rare-Earth-Neodymium-Magnets-p-997169.html

13-Sep-2017: Re-generated model from flat 2D dimensional design, in order to get all geometries exactly correct, and with some size adjustments after discussion with Chris. Added design notes in PDF form.

18-Sep-2017: Received first prints. All fitted perfectly. but arguably a bit 'snug' around the light switch, so I've added 1mm to the inner width to make it 87mm x 87mm inside. Overall I'm very pleased with the way this worked-out.

description.text:
This is my take on the Portal 2 Weighted Storage Cube. I designed it in SketchUp. It measures 7" x 7". This is complex model that requires almost 2 rolls of filament, electronics assembly, the Arduino platform, and some sanding and painting. You'll need, at minimum, an Arduino micro, 6 Adafruit Neopixel rings, and an accelerometer. You'll also need some 4-40 threaded inserts, some screws, and some tiny magnets. Several pieces need to be glued together. You could also forgo the use of the 4-40 screws and inserts for the LED holders and just glue the whole thing together. Your choice. Other electronics are also required: battery pack, prototype board, wires, etc. (See the 5-part blog on my website for more details. The link is below.)

It runs off a 3 x AA battery pack, although with 72 LEDs and an Arduino, the batteries do not last long at all. So feel free to improve the battery pack and/or power management.

The acrylic centers need to be laser cut. I've included the SVG file. The stencil for the Aperture Science logos also needs to be laser cut. That file has also been included. The Arduino code is also included. However, if you plan on implementing the electronics, you'll also need to download the Neopixel and MMA8451 libraries from Adafruit.com.

I have a 5-part blog post on my website detailing the design and assembly of the cube from start to finish. This may offer more instruction and guidance that can be detailed here. http://kevinrye.net/index_files/portal_cube_p1.php

I offer no tech support on this, so if you take this project on, it's on you to figure it out. Feel free to make any improvements you feel are necessary. Thanks for looking and happy building!

Printing the side panels face down on a raft makes a mess when peeling them away from the raft, and makes it that much harder to sand. Parts were printed face up with supports. This will result in you using twice the amount of material. You will burn through almost a whole roll just printing the 6 side panels. You'll need another roll, maybe 2, for all the corners, edges, bezels, and LED holders.

Corners printed one side down with supports and rafts.
Edges printed one side down with rafts.
LED holders printed face up with rafts.
Bezels were printed face up with rafts and support.
PCB mounts and base with rafts.

Post printing

Parts were sanded down to 400 grit, then primed with self-etching primer.
Parts were then painted with acrylic paint that was mixed to match. (dark gray and white) Paint was applied with a paint roller to give it a slight texture. It was then given a light sanding with 400 grit paper, and then sprayed with a matte clear coat.

Although the corners were secured with 4-40 threaded inserts and screws, some of the corners still wiggled a little bit. I went ahead and glued them down, along with the edges, with some Loctite 2-part plastic epoxy.

I remixed it because I sent a message to the maker (Dougwar) of the original asking if the separate parts are still available as I was fine with paying for the model in separate parts. But I never heard anything and decided to just remix it and post it for everyone use.

description.text:
I wanted to offset my fan like this so I could create a gap for viewing the print from the front of my MK2S printer. This design saved me a lot of time, I just added the gap.

I'm not entirely sure I like the exit design for the ducts, especially with an e3d sock. They are rather far from the extruded plastic, not directional, and partially blocked by the sock. That being said I just pulled a perfect 50mm bridge so it can't be all bad. I may alter the design further in the future, maybe not, we'll see.

I did a test print of both pieces (see the description in the original for the second piece) in PLA to check fit and function. I've printed several hours of PLA prints now and the heat doesn't seem to be bothering the parts... I may just use the PLA parts rather then remake them in ABS/PETG. We'll see if they hold up over time.

When you assemble this, put the two printed parts together first(this is key), then mount it on the printer, then mount the fan to it. To get the fan to reach without taking apart the whole cable whip, gently pull a little slack on the wires(you should be able to get a couple mm of extra length) then on the fan itself unhook the wire from the little plastic tab/guide.
